{"Body": "<!-- p.p1 {margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px; text-align: justify; font: 9.0px 'Whitney HTF SemiBold'} p.p2 {margin: 0.0px 0.0px 10.0px 0.0px; text-align: justify; font: 9.0px 'Whitney HTF'} p.p3 {margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px; text-align: justify; font: 9.0px 'Utopia Std'} p.p4 {margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px; text-align: justify; text-indent: 10.0px; font: 9.0px 'Utopia Std'} p.p5 {margin: 10.0px 0.0px 10.0px 0.0px; text-align: justify; font: 9.0px 'Whitney HTF'} p.p6 {margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px; text-align: justify; font: 9.0px 'Utopia Std'; min-height: 11.0px} span.s1 {font: 9.0px 'Whitney HTF'; letter-spacing: -0.1px} span.s2 {letter-spacing: -0.1px} -->By Ciaran Nolan -\u00a0Research Editor\n\nFianna Fail politicians were not the only ones resigning important posts last week, as Union of Students in Ireland Deputy president Conan \u00d3 Broin also announced his intention to resign his post in the national students&rsquo; union.\n\n\u00d3 Broin, a former Trinity student, who also held the position of Students&rsquo; Union president last academic year, said that he was to resign owing to a conflict of interest with a job offer he had received over the Christmas\n\ncampaign of Labour Councillor Robert Dowds. During his resignation speech he said that &ldquo;a conflict of interest now exists between my duties and responsibilities as Deputy President of USI and what is in my own personal interest&rdquo;.\n\n\u00d3 Broin said he made the decision after much consultation with close family and friends after he was offered the position. O&rsquo; Broin cited the flawed political system in Ireland as one of the main factors for his resignation, &ldquo;I have seen how flawed our national political system is and how crucial it is that we change the way we do our business in this country, The Labour Party has committed to making those radical changes in the lifetime of the next D\u00e1il&rdquo;.\n\n\u00d3 Broin will not be replaced as Deputy President, following the USI convention\u00a0 position will not be filled as it is over half way through the boards lifespan and instead his important workload consisting of campaigning for students and informing students of the political position of education in parties mandates, which is an extremely important task given the imminent March general election will be burdened by existing members of the board.\n\nOrganizations in opposition to the USI have reacted angrily to the resignation half way through his paid term. Aidan Rowe, a member of FEE in NUI Maynooth has described O&rsquo; Broins resignation as another example of politics intruding with students interests, &ldquo;I think his stepping down in order to take up a position within the Labour Party validates what FEE has said about the culture of student politics: that Student&rsquo;s Unions and USI are seen as stepping stones for students with political ambitions rather than as representative organizations for students.&rdquo; Stephanie Fleming, Welfare officer in Trinity Students Union also accused O&rsquo; Broin of having lost interest in the Trinity College Students Union after his election to USI.\n\nO&rsquo; Broin officially stepped down as Deputy President on Friday last. His name was removed from the signatories of the USI bank account and replaced with that of Eastern Area Officer John Logue.", "Imageurl": "<!-- p.p1 {margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px; text-align: justify; font: 9.0px 'Whitney HTF SemiBold'} p.p2 {margin: 0.0px 0.0px 10.0px 0.0px; text-align: justify; font: 9.0px 'Whitney HTF'} p.p3 {margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px; text-align: justify; font: 9.0px 'Utopia Std'} p.p4 {margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px; text-align: justify; text-indent: 10.0px; font: 9.0px 'Utopia Std'} p.p5 {margin: 10.0px 0.0px 10.0px 0.0px; text-align: justify; font: 9.0px 'Whitney HTF'} p.p6 {margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px; text-align: justify; font: 9.0px 'Utopia Std'; min-height: 11.0px} span.s1 {font: 9.0px 'Whitney HTF'; letter-spacing: -0.1px} span.s2 {letter-spacing: -0.1px} -->By Ciaran Nolan -\u00a0Research Editor\n\nFianna Fail politicians were not the only ones resigning important posts last week, as Union of Students in Ireland Deputy president Conan \u00d3 Broin also announced his intention to resign his post in the national students&rsquo; union.\n\n\u00d3 Broin, a former Trinity student, who also held the position of Students&rsquo; Union president last academic year, said that he was to resign owing to a conflict of interest with a job offer he had received over the Christmas\n\ncampaign of Labour Councillor Robert Dowds. During his resignation speech he said that &ldquo;a conflict of interest now exists between my duties and responsibilities as Deputy President of USI and what is in my own personal interest&rdquo;.\n\n\u00d3 Broin said he made the decision after much consultation with close family and friends after he was offered the position. O&rsquo; Broin cited the flawed political system in Ireland as one of the main factors for his resignation, &ldquo;I have seen how flawed our national political system is and how crucial it is that we change the way we do our business in this country, The Labour Party has committed to making those radical changes in the lifetime of the next D\u00e1il&rdquo;.\n\n\u00d3 Broin will not be replaced as Deputy President, following the USI convention\u00a0 position will not be filled as it is over half way through the boards lifespan and instead his important workload consisting of campaigning for students and informing students of the political position of education in parties mandates, which is an extremely important task given the imminent March general election will be burdened by existing members of the board.\n\nOrganizations in opposition to the USI have reacted angrily to the resignation half way through his paid term. Aidan Rowe, a member of FEE in NUI Maynooth has described O&rsquo; Broins resignation as another example of politics intruding with students interests, &ldquo;I think his stepping down in order to take up a position within the Labour Party validates what FEE has said about the culture of student politics: that Student&rsquo;s Unions and USI are seen as stepping stones for students with political ambitions rather than as representative organizations for students.&rdquo; Stephanie Fleming, Welfare officer in Trinity Students Union also accused O&rsquo; Broin of having lost interest in the Trinity College Students Union after his election to USI.\n\nO&rsquo; Broin officially stepped down as Deputy President on Friday last. His name was removed from the signatories of the USI bank account and replaced with that of Eastern Area Officer John Logue.", "Thumb_nail": "http://universitytimes.ie/wp-content/uploads/2013/utlogo.jpg", "ID": "251", "Heading": "\u00d3 Broin resigns USI post"}